The functions that append a write statement to the bulk (e.g. [{{mongoc_bulk_operation_insert()}}|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/1.6.0/src/mongoc/mongoc-bulk-operation.c#L297], [{{mongoc_bulk_operation_replace_one()}}|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/1.6.0/src/mongoc/mongoc-bulk-operation.c#L373]) inconsistently handle error reporting.

If we look at [{{mongoc_bulk_operation_insert()}}|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/1.6.0/src/mongoc/mongoc-bulk-operation.c#L297], {{_mongoc_validate_new_document()}} is only called if a document is being appended to a newly initialized insert command, and even then the validation function's boolean return value is ignored and a potentially invalid document is still added to the command. Validation is never performed at all before appending to an existing insert command (i.e. {{_mongoc_write_command_insert_append()}}).

[{{mongoc_bulk_operation_replace_one()}}|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/1.6.0/src/mongoc/mongoc-bulk-operation.c#L373] delegates to {{_mongoc_bulk_operation_replace_one_with_opts()}}, which starts with the following logic: 

{code}
if (bulk->result.error.domain) {
   /* already failed e.g. a bad call to mongoc_bulk_operation_insert */
   RETURN (true);
}
{code}

This logic prevents a later {{_mongoc_validate_replace()}} call from overwriting a previous error, which is good, but it effectively makes {{mongoc_bulk_operation_replace_one()}} a NOP with no way to indicate that to the user. It would be better to return false if there is a pre-existing error. Also, the insert and update paths are missing equivalent logic (i.e. NOP on a pre-existing error) entirely, which means they may overwrite a previous error.

When doing a pipe on cursor with an error in query, there is no way to know about this error, even if you are subscribed to 'error' event on cursor. Instead, a runtime error is thrown with the following stacktrace:

{noformat}
Error: Cannot switch to old mode now.
    at emitDataEvents (_stream_readable.js:730:11)
    at Readable.pause (_stream_readable.js:721:3)
    at Cursor.destroy (/home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/lib/cursor.js:697:8)
    at /home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/lib/cursor.js:735:31
    at handleCallback (/home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/lib/utils.js:95:12)
    at /home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/lib/cursor.js:419:20
    at handleCallback (/home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/node_modules/mongodb-core/lib/cursor.js:234:5)
    at /home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/node_modules/mongodb-core/lib/cursor.js:535:22
    at queryCallback (/home/weekens/workspace/saymon/backend/server/node_modules/mongodb/node_modules/mongodb-core/lib/cursor.js:170:14)
    at b (domain.js:183:18)
{noformat}

This also concerns any error, that can happen during diver<->DB communication. Query error is only for the sake of simplicity.

Sample code to reproduce the problem:

{code:javascript}
var cursor = mongoDb.collection('myCollection').find({
  timestamp: { $ltx: request.params.maxTimestamp } // Error in query.
});

cursor.on('error', function(err) {
  log.error('DB query failed:' + err);

  next(err);
});

cursor.pipe(response); // Runtime error is thrown, 'error' event is not triggered.
{code}

Wasn't tested on Node v0.12, but _stream_readable.js code in Node v0.12 contains the same error condition, so, the problem is likely to reproduce in Node v0.12 as well.

I've found this bug through an issue I'm having with Mongoid, so I'm not 100% sure if this is an issue with BSON, or that Mongoid is using it wrong.

Consider the following code:
{code:example.rb}
attributes = BSON::Document.new
attributes["test"] = nil
(attributes["test"] ||= {}).merge!({"test" => "test})
# You'd expect attributes["test"] to be {"test" => "test"} 
# here, but it's actually {}
{code}

The last line is found in Mongoid here: https://github.com/mongodb/mongoid/blob/master/lib/mongoid/attributes.rb#L179 and (I think) is the result is causing issues like this: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29899935/mongoid-localized-field-not-being-set-in-first-form-submission

It works fine if you make {{attributes}} a Hash instead, so I presume it's something the way {{||=}} or {{merge!}} are implemented in BSON::Document?

Writing my example differently, e.g.
{code:example.rb}
attributes = BSON::Document.new
attributes["test"] = nil
attributes["test"] ||= {}
attributes["test"].merge!({"test" => "test})
{code}

also works as expected.

